What the River Already Knew
In the year 2150, José Lanz was sent backward through eleven and a half centuries to murder a song.

The Council had explained it to him the way they explained everything—through glass, in the cold lavender light of the Archive, with their faces flattened into the patience of people who have never once been wrong. The world they governed had been built on a single foundational hymn, El Canto del Hombre que Volvió, the Song of the Man Who Returned. Every law was a verse of it. Every silence between citizens was a rest in its measure. The historians had traced the song's first breath to a particular village on the Orinoco delta, in the year 1000, and they had decided, after much glass and much patience, that if the song had never been sung, the world might have turned out kinder. Softer. Less like a cage with very good acoustics.

So they chose José. A pardo from Maracaibo by ancestry, brown as wet clay, with his grandmother's tight black coils and a wiry, restless frame that had never sat still through a single briefing. They chose him because he was a writer by temperament and a coward by training, and they believed a man who loved words would know how to strangle one in its cradle.

He stepped out of the chamber and into the year 1000, and the heat hit him like a wet hand pressed over his whole body.

The delta was green in a way 2150 had forgotten green could be—not the manicured green of the bio-domes but a riotous, dripping, insolent green that climbed over everything and demanded to be looked at. Moriche palms leaned across the water like gossiping elders. The river itself was the color of strong coffee with too much milk, sliding past in a slow brown muscle, and the air smelled of mud and smoke and ripe fruit gone soft. Macaws tore across the sky in screaming ribbons of scarlet and gold. On the bank, lifted above the flood-line on stilts of dark wood, stood the village: a cluster of palafitos, open-sided houses thatched with palm, their floors swaying gently over the water as children ran across them, sure-footed as cats.

They found him within the hour. Of course they did. A stranger does not hide on a river that everyone reads like a face.

The woman who came to him first was named Daurama. He would learn that name later; in the moment she was only a presence—tall, broad through the shoulders, her dark eyes moving over his strange clothes and his stranger fear with an intelligence that made him want to confess to crimes he had not yet committed. She fed him first and questioned him after, which told him more about her people than any of the Archive's tidy paragraphs ever had.

He had a plan. The plan was simple, the way all doomed plans are.

There was, the historians had told him, a man in this village—a singer, a keeper of stories—who within the year would compose the first verse of the Canto. José needed only to find him before the song was born and discredit him, dishonor him, make the village stop their ears against him. Sour the soil so the seed could not take. He had rehearsed it for months. He would tell them the truth. He would tell them that a song was coming that would one day grow teeth and devour the future, and that they must refuse it.

He told them.

He stood on the swaying floor of the largest palafito, with the river breathing beneath him and the whole village gathered in the firelight, and he told them everything. He told them he had come from a time so distant it had no name they could hold. He told them of the towers of cold light and the Council behind glass and the hymn that ruled it all. He told them that a song would be born here, on this water, from one of their own mouths, and that it would travel down the centuries like a sickness, and that they must never, ever sing it. His voice cracked. The macaws had gone quiet. The fire spat. He had never in his life spoken so well.

When he finished, an old man near the fire—not the singer he had come to stop, just an old man with river-water eyes—began, very softly, to hum.

It was a melody José did not recognize. It was being invented in front of him, note by hesitant note, as the old man reached for a shape that would hold the impossible thing the stranger had just said. A man came back across all the water and all the years to warn us of ourselves. The hum found words. The words found rhythm. By the time the moon was high the children had the chorus, and by the time José understood what he was hearing it was already too late, it had always been too late, the thing had teeth before it had a second verse.

He had not come to prevent the song.

He was the song.

There was no singer he had arrived too early to stop. There had never been one. The first verse of El Canto del Hombre que Volvió was not about a man who returned in some general, mythic sense. It was about him—the stranger from across the water, brown as wet clay, who stood on the swaying floor and begged them to forget what he was teaching them to remember. The historians in their lavender light had read the lyrics for a thousand years and never once recognized the man in the mirror, because the man in the mirror was a coward they had bred and trained and pointed backward like a loaded gun, and the trigger had been the words you must never sing this.

He stayed eleven days. He could not stop them singing; he could only sit by the fire and listen to his own arrival become scripture. Daurama watched him go gray with the understanding of it and said nothing, because she had understood it before he opened his mouth, the way the river understands the rain before it falls.

When the chamber pulled him home, he expected to find a changed 2150—a softer one, a kinder cage, some flicker of the world the Council had hoped to buy with his crime.

He found his own world exactly as he had left it.

The towers of cold light. The glass. The hymn in every silence. Nothing had moved by the width of a single note, because nothing could have; the song had needed him to exist, and so he had existed, and so he had gone, and so the song was sung, and so the world stood precisely as it stood, balanced on the back of a paradox that had never once wobbled. He had not failed to change the past. He had completed it. The future he hated was not a problem he had been sent to solve. It was a problem that had invented him—reached back across eleven and a half centuries, brown hands and curled hair and trained cowardice, to make sure the river got the verse it had always already sung.

The Council brought him back behind the glass and asked him, in the patient lavender light, whether the mission had been a success.

José Lanz thought of the macaws. He thought of the slow brown muscle of the Orinoco and the houses that swayed like cradles over the water and an old man humming a shape around the impossible. He thought of Daurama, who had known.

"It worked perfectly," he said. "It always had."

